I used to think Pilates were for fancy blonde actresses who wanted to do dumb tortuous things for no good reason other than to be like Gwyneth Paltrow. 

(Which, depending on who you are, might be a perfectly good reason. No judgment here.)

Now I KNOW that Pilates is for ANYone who wants to feel INSTANTLY more aligned, strong and - yes - slightly tortured. (But in the best way.)

I recently swapped one training session per week for Pilates and it has been SO good for my overall fitness, recovery and alignment…AND my sense of accomplishment! 

I am constantly amazed by what can be done with this medieval torture device. It. Is. Genius. 

For my @athleticmomprogram crew - we’re going to work some mat Pilates in to the program in the future! No torture device required! 

I don’t know how I got so lucky to have @nick_briney as my trainer and @britnibriney as my Pilates instructor, but I’m sure happy I do! Their biz @evexiakc has it all, Kansas City folks 😊 

Who else out there loves Pilates?!
#liztalksfitness

See how many times I had to stop, regroup, shake it out, and yes, even stall a little 😉 before getting back into it in today’s session with coach @britnibriney?

Every now and then, a workout should humble you.

This shouldn’t be EVERY workout, of course, let alone every movement session. But there is a time and a place for un petit struggle. 

So many people think that because they once over-exercised, that they can never challenge themselves again. While some folks DO need to back off, take it easy, and stay gentle, MANY of us need a little kick in the tush sometimes. The important thing is: knowing YOURSELF. Tuning in to YOUR body’s cues. Staying curious about what you might be capable of. Being watchful of the distinction between being gentle with yourself and falling victim to inertia. 

Do you agree? 

FYI, I carry lots of marginally offensive metaphors around in my brain about how little most of us know of physical struggle. One of them is “it’s not John-McCain-in-a-prison-camp ‘hard.’ It’s PILATES.” 🫣 Another one is “it’s not trekking-through-a-jungle-for-days-after-your-plane-crashes-into-the-side-of-a-mountain ‘hard.’ It’s EXERCISE.” (If you listened to Liz Talks Podcast #52, you’d know what I mean by that last one 😉)

All I’m saying is … it’s not a bad thing to feel like a jackass sometimes. And the jackass threshold is highly individual. I’m just suggesting you determine yours. 😁 

#liztalksfitness

Not my regular stuff, but … 

My friend had this left on her car today. She was having a hard day already. 

Look, I’ve left notes on peoples’ cars before. But I figure if I’m gonna do it, I’ll at least have the courage to sign my name … and, in some cases, give contact info in case the accused wants to talk it out. And if I don’t want to do that, guess what? I don’t get to throw a tantrum on a post-it. 

Say it in the street? That’s a knockout. Say it in a tweet - er, scrap of paper - that’s a cop out. 

If the person in St. Augustine, FL who left this note steps in soggy dog poop today, I hope they know why. 

Thoughts? Have you ever gotten (or left) one of these?

Have you heard of “relaxation induced anxiety?” 🤯 It’s a thing! #messymeditators 😮

Lack of interest in meat? Your stomach acid could be to blame! Read on…

In episode 408 of the @balancedbitespodcast (the VEGAN/CARNIVORE episode you’ve been waiting for!) I chat with @michelleshapirord about what your body is REALLY asking for when it’s saying “no, thanks” to meat.

We tackle LOTS more in this episode - from our personal reasons for dabbling in vegan dieting and where vegan and carnivore diets are actually similar (yes, for real)!

Listen on Spotify, Apple, or anywhere you get your podcasts! There’s also a link in my bio.

Show your support for this episode and all the tough-topic-tackling by leaving a comment or a review!

Let me be clear: there are a LOT of different “diets” people utilize to attempt to achieve an aesthetic that they deem “worthy.” I bounced in and out of a LOT of “diets” to attempt to beat my body into submission. Vegan dieting was just one of them. (And, no. I didn’t do it “correctly.” I drank veggie broth and ate bean soup.)

In episode 408 of the @balancedbitespodcast, @realfoodliz (that’s me!) and @michelleshapirord talk Vegan/Carnivore and the many mental hoops we jump through to justify disordered eating. 

(If you’re gonna come in hot on this, can I humbly request you listen to the full episode, and not just a sound byte from it? 😁)

Anthony’s own experience healing his extreme, years long migraine disorder led him to create the Head Health app, which aims to guide migraine sufferers through an evidence-backed, multi-dimensional, non-triggering healing process. His success has been amazing!

You can experience the app by going to @headhealthco. You’ll find a data-driven, individualized environment backed by former migraine sufferers (including their resident neuroscientist). On this week’s episode, Steph interviews Liz Wolfe @realfoodliz, a Nutritional Therapy Practitioner, best-selling author, and cofounder of the Athletic Mom Program @athleticmomprogram. Athletic Mom helps moms (and ANYONE who needs the most efficient and impactful workouts possible) to own their inner athlete and feel better in their body. Liz and Steph talk about challenges and opportunities in motherhood including disconnecting from social media, avoiding the comparison trap, prioritizing protein, and mindful movement as we age. If you’re interested in finding a way to make healthy eating and movement stick, without buying into the toxic “fitness/wellness” culture, you won’t want to miss this.

Topics Discussed: 
🕑Taking time away from social media
🧭Losing yourself after having kids
❓Why all moms are athletes
📅Mobility in mid- to late-30s
🐄Prioritizing protein as a mom
🏋How to build an effective home workout

🎙 To listen to today’s episode, head on over to our website doctormompodcast.com, iTunes, Stitcher, Spotify or any podcast app! For a direct link, click the link in my bio!

S2 E3 of Quiet the Diet is LIVE! This episode is all about the Evolution of the Paleo Diet with the OG Paleo Queens (and my dear darling friends @realfoodliz @stephgreunke) 

I know for myself that the Paleo diet was my gateway diet into the magic that functional medicine has to offer. It was the first time I started to shift my understanding of diets as being something for weight loss and into something that could be healing. Im@so grateful for the Paleo diet and it’s creators and perpetuators for that!!!! 

And at the same time, I now see a paleo diet being overly recommended as a very long term elimination diet, which raises some concerns. And as Liz beautifully states in this clip from the episode, being “perfect paleo” either for a societal reason or for a health reason can manifest as orthorexic symptoms. 

We can’t fear food, even if the food “inflames” us. 

It was my HONOR to have these brilliant nutrition professionals on the pod and this is a MUST listen!

“I am” is a powerful phrase. 

Now, I’m all about acceptance. Radically accepting ourselves and our realities. But there’s a huge difference between acceptance and identifying with our captor; between “naming” something…and labeling ourselves. 

Accepting ourselves, our challenges, our experiences SO THAT WE CAN MOVE THROUGH THEM as best we can, to live the best lives possible, is 🔑 

When you’ve started to label yourself, and limit your experiences based on that label, you’ve crossed over from *acceptance and naming* to *identification (with your “condition” or “captor”) and labeling.*

The chat Ms. Fab and I had, particularly about failure, hit HARD. I have been chronically failure-averse and I struggle to help my own kids embrace failure. I need ideas, for myself and for them!

If you ever get that inkling that your kids’ education might be missing something - or even if you wonder what you can do at HOME to keep that spark of curiosity alive - LISTEN AND GRAB THIS BOOK!
